<Document>
<name>Transalpina — DN67C</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Transalpina — DN67C</h2><p><i>Romania · DN67C across the Parâng Mountains, Sebeș to Novaci</i></p><p><b>Higher than Transfăgărășan and emptier — Pasul Urdele at 2,145 m is Romania's highest paved pass.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>88 km (55 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Late June–October</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Closes November–mid June, sheep flocks of hundreds, fog, weather changes in minutes, no fuel for 60 km stretches</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>181</td></tr></table><hr><p>Higher and lonelier than the Transfăgărășan. Pasul Urdele at 2,145 m is the highest paved pass in Romania. Locals call it 'Drumul Regelui' (the King's Road) because King Carol II ordered it built in 1934–35; it was paved only in 2010–14 and remains one of Europe's least-trafficked high-alpine roads. Wildflowers in July; sheep flocks of 1,000+ at any season. Long stretches with no services, no cell, no traffic. The DN67C runs roughly parallel to the Transfăgărășan, about 80 km west — easy to combine the two passes into a single Carpathian-crossing trip.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Lake Oașa</b> — High-altitude reservoir at 1,250 m. Forest road accesses fishing pullouts; popular for shorter walks.</li><li><b>Obârșia Lotrului</b> — Where the Jiu and Lotru watersheds meet, with a small chapel and seasonal restaurants. Base for hiking the Parâng ridges.</li><li><b>Pasul Urdele</b> — 2,145 m — highest paved pass in Romania. Treeline well below; alpine meadows and rocky outcrops. Sheep-droving season runs July–September.</li><li><b>Rânca</b> — Alpine ski resort on the south side of the pass — a single chairlift, a few hotels, base for summer hiking and mountain biking.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
